---
import ContentPage from '../layouts/ContentPage.astro';
import { languageAlternates } from '../lib/i18n';

const description =
  'Making production agents safe enough to leave running: tests you trust, limits on what they can do, monitoring, and a rollback people will actually use.';

const alternates = languageAlternates('/agent-reliability/', '/de/agenten-zuverlaessigkeit/');

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebPage',
  '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/agent-reliability/#webpage',
  url: 'https://larsullrich.de/agent-reliability/',
  name: 'Agent reliability',
  description,
  inLanguage: 'en',
  isPartOf: { '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/#website' },
  about: {
    '@type': 'DefinedTerm',
    name: 'Agent reliability',
    description,
  },
  author: { '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/#person' },
};
---

<ContentPage
  title="Agent reliability - Lars Ullrich"
  description={description}
  canonical="/agent-reliability/"
  noteId="agent-reliability"
  heading="Agent reliability"
  eyebrow="Practice"
  lead="A demo agent is a party trick. A production agent has to keep working when nobody is watching."
  icon="/graphics/icon-focus-monitor.svg"
  alternates={alternates}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  localeSwitch={{ href: '/de/agenten-zuverlaessigkeit/', label: 'Deutsch' }}
>
  <p>
    In a demo, someone asks a question and everyone claps. In production the agent runs on its own, again and again, against messy live data. That's when you get loops, made-up actions, bills that spike overnight, or quiet quality drops nobody notices for a week.
  </p>
  <p>
    Reliability is the boring stuff that stops that. Tests you run before and after changes. Hard limits on what the agent can touch and spend. Monitoring for drift and loops. A rollback path the team will actually hit when things go sideways. Most teams skip this part. Then they wonder why the demo didn't survive contact with Monday morning.
  </p>

  <h2>How I usually approach it</h2>
  <p>
    First we check whether you even need an agent. Plenty of problems want a simpler pipeline. If an agent still makes sense, we design for cost and failure modes up front, then ship and harden. For teams that already went live, the Reliability Retainer covers the keep-it-running work, including an
    <a href="/eu-ai-act-readiness/">EU AI Act</a>
    re-check when usage or the rules move.
  </p>
  <p>
    Don't know where to begin?
    <a href="/services/readiness-audit/">Start with the audit</a>.
    More context in
    <a href="/work/patterns/">patterns</a>
    and
    <a href="/fractional-cto-caio/">fractional CTO / CAIO</a>.
  </p>
</ContentPage>
